I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and establishing connections with artists. They don't have that pressure of having to examine everything through a critical, colored lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but now, this collective awareness has disappeared.
Back then, we could directly immerse ourselves in the content without worrying about its source, because tracing the origin was not easy in those days.
We regarded these artists as deities, and there was no reason to question this worship. Thus, we established a "pseudosocial relationship" with them, viewing it as an indispensable part of life.
This also explains why we are so fascinated with nostalgia.
When the TV show "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to binge-watch it while eating pizza.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows on streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When discussing the plot on social media, people often add a "spoiler alert" or simply communicate within specific groups.
Unconsciously, we all long for that sense of collective belonging that used to connect everyone.
It's precisely this nostalgia that makes us rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "The Candidate," whose unforgettable lines spread online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the works and believe most people would understand them instantly.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume everyone has seen it.
Nowadays, with information exploding, there are just too many things that require our attention, making it impossible to streamline... Do we still have a chance to get rid of this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out that they are either notorious sexual predators or stubborn bigots full of prejudices, and this cycle is exhausting.
On one hand, we are immersed in nostalgia, but on the other hand, we have to admit that the people who created the artworks we love might have serious moral flaws, and this contradictory mentality leaves us feeling helpless.
We will be more careful in establishing "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that if a person wants to gain wealth and power, it is hard to ensure that he or she will not hurt or exploit others.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have formed a class consciousness, which helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who are stubborn and insist on putting others on a pedestal; when the idol falls, they pretend to be shocked.
We are in an era of change, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
